Telecom Customer Churn Prediction

Jahnavi Saikia

April 26, 2019

Problem Statement

Churning in the telecom industry implies customers changing the service providers. In telecom domain where the customer acquisition has higher cost than customer retention and where there is a rampant price war, it becomes important to predict and profile the customer behavior and predict them so that offers can be rolled out to retain them prior to switching.

Objective

1. Exploring the the data through visualization to understand the current state and various factors (or combination of factors) which is contributing to customer churn.

2. Develop a prediction algorithm to predict customer churn.

3. Model evaluation and explaination of the metrics chosen for the model.

4. What extra features could have made the model better and give a better explanation of the factors leading to churn

5. Based on the descriptive analytics and model results try to come up with a strategy to arrest customer churn.

Data provided consist of the various behavior of customers and the last column states if the customer is still with the existing telecom company or not.

  2. Total evening minutes:-Customers churned show a higher Q1, Q3 & IQR indicating ithat usage of total evening minues possibly is a significant factor in this scenario.
  3. Total night minutes:-There is no significant difference in usage of night minutes between Churned vs Non Churned customers.

Analysis of Model performance

#Calculating Accuracy of prediction
accuracy= sum(diag(tab_mat)) / sum(tab_mat)
accuracy
## [1] 0.8694869
#calculating sensitivity TP/(TP+FN)
sensitivity=22/(22+141)
sensitivity
## [1] 0.1349693
#Calculating Specificity TN/TN+FP
specificity=929/(929+20)
specificity
## [1] 0.9789252
  1. The prediction of the above model is 85.5% accurate
  2. Sensitivity 13.4% is very low which implies that we were able to identify only 22 churned customers out of 163 correctly
  3. Specificity of 97.8% implies that the model has performed very well in predicting customers that are not churned.It could predict 929 out of 949 values correctly.

Since our aim is to predict the churned customer we will work on improving the model. Plotting ROC curve

library(ROCR)
## Loading required package: gplots
## 
## Attaching package: 'gplots'
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     lowess
res<-predict(model,train,type = "response")
ROCRpred=prediction(res,train$Churn)
ROCRperf<-performance(ROCRpred,"tpr","fpr")
plot(ROCRperf,colorize=TRUE,print.cutoffs.at=seq(0.1,by=0.1))

From ROC graph the new threshold is 0.2

Create confusion matrix with new threshold (0.2)

res.logit<-predict(model,test,type = "response")

Conclusion:

  1. Out of all the models (Logistic Regression, Decision Tree & Random Forest) to predict customers that will be churned, Random Forest stood out to be the best fit for this business case.
  2. The model could predict Churned customers with an accuracy of 72.5%
  3. The model also predicted "Not Churned customers with 98.7% confidence. Overall accuracy of the model stood at 95%
